    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"goblin's basket\" is a colloquialism I've used to describe a simple yet effective technique for managing scope creep. It's not a formal framework, but rather a metaphorical approach to categorizing features and requests.\n\nImagine a basket where you can place three types of items: \"Must-Haves,\" \"Should-Haves,\" and \"Nice-to-Haves.\" When stakeholders request new features or changes, you can place them in one of these baskets. \"Must-Haves\" are the essential features that align with the project's goals and deliverables. \"Should-Haves\" are features that are important but not critical to the project's success. \"Nice-to-Haves\" are features that are nice to have, but not essential.\n\nBy categorizing requests in this way, you can prioritize the project's goals and focus on delivering the \"Must-Haves\" first. This approach helps you manage scope creep by ensuring that you're not getting bogged down in non-essential features that might derail the project's momentum.\n\nThe term \"goblin's basket\" comes from the idea that goblins are notorious for accumulating shiny objects and treasures, but they often can't decide what's truly valuable. Similarly, stakeholders might request features",
      "source": "target",
